INTRODUCTION

The main goal now is to examine and understand the variations in usage styles between annual members and casual cyclists. The study intends to shed light on how these two user groups use the bike-sharing services offered by Cyclistic in various ways. The final objective is to use these insights to create a focused marketing plan that aims to turn occasional riders into yearly subscribers. The analysis will be supported by data from previous bike trips, and the conclusions will be vital in guiding Cyclistic’s data-driven decision-making.

This commercial endeavor supports Cyclistic’s strategic goal of increasing the number of annual subscriptions because it has been determined that these members are more profitable than casual riders. The analysis will serve as the basis for suggestions to improve the business’s marketing initiatives and promote annual membership growth.

The insights drawn from the study will directly influence Cyclistic’s marketing plan. These data will specifically lead the formulation of a marketing plan meant to turn casual riders into yearly subscribers. Here is how business decisions will be affected the outcomes:

Segmented marketing: Cyclistic executive team may improve its marketing efforts by comprehending the variations in usage patterns between annual members and casual riders. For instance, incentives and promotions can be created to specifically target casual riders based on their requirements and preferences.

Pricing and Membership Plans: Cyclistic executive team can improve its pricing strategies and membership plans by learning more about the reasons casual cyclists might think about purchasing annual subscriptions. This can entail developing more enticing membership plans that align with the interests of casual riders.

Brief background and summary of case study company

Cyclistic is a bike-share company in Chicago. It has a fleet of over 5,800 bicycles and 692 stations across the city. Cyclistic’s customers can purchase single-ride passes, full-day passes, or annual memberships. Single-ride passes and full-day passes are popular with casual riders, while annual memberships are popular with people who use Cyclistic bikes on a regular basis.

Cyclistic’s director of marketing, Lily Moreno, believes that the company’s future success depends on maximizing the number of annual members. Therefore, she has assigned her team to analyze the data to identify how annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently. This information will be used to design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members.

ASK PHASE

The problem we are trying to solve in the Cyclistic scenario is understanding how annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently. This understanding is crucial to designing a marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members effectively. Our insights will drive business decisions by providing data-driven recommendations for designing a marketing strategy. By understanding the differences in bike usage between these two customer groups, Cyclistic can tailor its marketing efforts to target casual riders more effectively and encourage them to become annual members.

Business Task

The business task is to analyze and compare the bike usage patterns of annual members and casual riders. This analysis will provid e insights into how these customer segments differ in their usage of Cyclistic bikes.

By comparing their usage patterns, we aim to identify key differences and insights that can inform the design of a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members.

Consider key stakeholders

Lily Moreno (Director of Marketing) Responsible for overseeing all marketing initiatives at Cyclistic, including the development of campaigns and strategies to promote the bike-share program.

Cyclistic Marketing Analytics Team A group of data analysts responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that informs Cyclistic’s marketing strategy. They work collaboratively to leverage data-driven insights in shaping marketing efforts.

Cyclistic Executive Team A group of high-level decision-makers within the company who have the authority to approve or reject the recommended marketing program. They are known for being detail-oriented and have a significant impact on the overall direction of the company.

Annual Members A user’s who have purchased annual memberships, providing them with long-term access to the bike-sharing service. They are committed users who contribute significantly to Cyclistic’s revenue.

Casual Riders An individual who uses Cyclistic’s bike-sharing services on a non-membership basis, such as purchasing single-ride passes or full-day passes. They are not committed annual members but represent a significant portion of Cyclistic’s user base.

Data Sources

To begin preparing the data, I accessed the Cyclistic trip data from a dedicated website repository that provides access to historical trip records. This repository is the source of our data.

https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html

The Cyclistic trip data is thoughtfully organized into multiple CSV files, one for each quarter of the year. These files are in table format and contain detailed information about individual bike trips. Key attributes include trip start and end times, station locations, user types (annual members and casual riders), and other trip-related details. This dataset will be instrumental in answering our business question.

Historical data on bike trips taken by Cyclistic customers. It is organized in tabular format with columns representing attributes such as trip duration, start and end stations, bike types, user types (annual member or casual rider), and timestamps.

PROCESS PHASE

During the “Process” phase, our primary goal was to ensure that the Cyclistic trip data, which serves as the foundation of our analysis, was well prepared and transformed to meet the highest standards of data quality and readiness. This approach involved the installation of essential R packages, the loading of libraries, and loading of historical trip data for multiple months. Column names were checked for consistency, and the structure of data frames was examined to understand data types. Date and time data were transformed and standardized for uniformity. The datasets were combined into a single unified dataset, with columns renamed for improved clarity. Additionally, feature engineering was applied to create new columns for day of the week, month, time, and trip duration. Data cleaning steps were taken to remove rows with negative trip durations, NULL values, and those related to test rides. We also take a data quality check ensuring that the dataset contained only two customer types. These preparation and cleaning processes have yielded a clean, reliable dataset ready for in-depth analysis, setting the stage for meaningful insights and informed decision-making in the subsequent phases of the case study.

ANALYZE & SHARE PHASE

In this phase, we leverage our carefully prepared dataset, df_processed_v2, containing trip records from multiple months, to gain meaningful insights into Cyclistic’s bike trips. During the data preparation phase, we standardized date and time formats and introduced new columns for day of the week, month, time, and trip duration, setting the stage for analysis. To extract insights, we’ll perform various calculations, including mean and maximum ride length, and determine the mode of weekdays to identify popular riding days. We’ll analyze data patterns, discover trends, and draw conclusions, all of which will be summarized in a deliverable. This summary will serve as the basis for data-driven recommendations as we progress through the case study.

Analysis Steps

Our analysis will entail segmenting the data into two groups: annual members and casual riders. For both groups, we’ll calculate descriptive statistics, such as mean and median trip duration, trip frequency, and usage patterns (weekdays vs. weekends). To effectively convey our findings, we’ll create informative visualizations like bar charts, line graphs, and heat maps, facilitating comparisons between annual members and casual riders and highlighting differences and trends. If needed, hypothesis tests may be employed to assess the statistical significance of observed distinctions. Ultimately, we will present key findings, emphasizing disparities and commonalities in how these two user groups utilize Cyclistic bikes. These insights will shape our marketing strategy recommendations, providing actionable guidance for converting casual riders into annual members.

summary(df_processed_v2$trip_duration)
  Min.     1st Qu.   Median     Mean    3rd Qu.     Max.
  0.00     5.45      9.60      18.36    17.10    51461.40 
df_processed_v2 %>% 
  group_by(customer_type) %>% 
  summarise(min_trp_duration = min(trip_duration),max_trp_duration = max(trip_duration), median_trp_duration = median(trip_duration),
mean_trp_duration = mean(trip_duration))

These summary statistics give you insights into how trip durations differ between “casual” and “member” customers. We observed that both “casual” and “member” customers can have very short trips, with a minimum trip duration of 0 minutes. This indicates that some cyclist, regardless of their type, use our services for quick trips. The “Casual” customers can have significantly longer trips, with a maximum trip duration reaching as high as 51461.400 minutes. In contrast, “member” customers tend to have shorter trips, with a maximum duration of 1559.667 minutes. This suggests that “casual” customers are more likely to use our services for extended journeys. The median trip duration for “casual” customers is approximately 11.85 minutes, while for “member” customers, it’s approximately 8.51 minutes. On average, “casual” customers have longer trips, with an average trip duration of approximately 28.14 minutes, compared to “member” customers, who have an average trip duration of approximately 12.38 minutes.

Visualization1

df_processed_v2 %>% group_by(customer_type, day_of_week) %>%   
  summarise(number_of_rides = n()) %>% 
  arrange(customer_type, day_of_week) %>%    
  ggplot(aes(x = day_of_week, y = number_of_rides, fill = customer_type)) +    
  labs(title = "Total trips by customer type Vs. Day of the week", 
       fill = "Customer Type") +   
  geom_col(width = 0.5, position = position_dodge(width = 0.5)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE)) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("skyblue", "yellow"))

Observation - Members use the bike-share service more than casual riders on weekdays, especially from Monday to Friday. However, casual riders use the service more on weekends, with the highest usage on Saturdays and the lowest usage on Sundays. This means that members are the main users of the bike-share service on weekdays, while casual riders are the main users on weekends

# Create the ggplot chart 
df_processed_v2 %>%   group_by(customer_type, month) %>%   
  summarise(number_of_rides = n()) %>%   arrange(customer_type, month) %>%   
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = number_of_rides, fill = customer_type)) +

  labs(title = "Total trips by customer type Vs. Month", 
       x = "Moth",

  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30)) +   
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("skyblue", "yellow"))

Observation - The graph shows a clear upward trend in usage over time, proving an increase in the service’s popularity as a go-to form of transportation for both members and non-members. The consistent increase indicates that numerous individuals are embracing this mode of transportation. It is also obvious that the number of members who ride constantly exceeds the number of casual riders. This variation might be caused by users using the service frequently, depending on it for commuting, or preferring it during peak times. The data also shows which months of the year experience the highest and lowest levels of ridership. Due to the better weather and more outside activities, June and May are the busiest months for both members and casual riders. However, there are fewer riders in December and January, maybe as a result of the colder climate and altered travel patterns during the holidays.

Observation - Casual riders have a longer average route duration than members, but this does not necessarily mean that they cover twice as much distance. This is because casual riders are more likely to take shorter trips, such as commuting to and from work or school. The graph shows a clear upward trend in the average travel duration for both members and non-members from Monday to Sunday. This could be due to a number of factors, including the likelihood that people have more free time on weekends and are more likely to use the service for longer trips like sightseeing tours or travels to discover new places. Casual riders have longer trips than members because they are more likely to take short trips, such as commuting to and from work or school.

Visualization 5

# Create the ggplot chart 
df_processed_v2 %>% 
  group_by(customer_type, time) %>% 
  summarise(number_of_trips = n()) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = time, y = number_of_trips, color = customer_type, group = customer_type)) + geom_line() + 
  scale_x_datetime(date_breaks = "1 hour", minor_breaks = NULL, date_labels = "%H:%M", expand = c(0, 0)) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + 
  labs(title = "Demand over 24 hours of a day", 
       x = "Time of the day", 
       y = "Number of Trips",
       fill = "Customer Type") + 
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("skyblue", "yellow"))

Observation - Highest demand occurs during morning (7am - 9am) and evening (5pm - 7pm) rush hours. Likely due to commuting, work/school, errands, and socializing. Lowest demand is during early morning (1am - 5am) and late night (11pm - 1am) hours. Casual customers have higher demand during rush hours. Member customers have higher demand during off-peak hours (10am - 4pm, 8pm - 10pm). While Member customers have more flexibility and prefer non-peak hours to avoid crowds. This illustrates a consistent demand pattern driven by factors like commuting, work schedules, and social activities.

Open Tableau.

Count unique start_lat and start_lng for casual riders targeted in marketing efforts.

  1. Connect to Data: Start by connecting Tableau to DF_PROCESS_V2.csv dataset.

  2. Filter for Casual Riders: Create a filter to exclude rows where customer_type is like “casual.”

  3. Aggregation: To count the occurrences of unique combinations of start_lat and start_lng, we need to create a calculated field that combines these two dimensions. In Tableau, you can create a calculated field as follows:

    • Go to Analysis menu -> Create Calculated Field.

    • Name the calculated field LatLongCount

    • Enter the following formula to concatenate start_lat and start_lng:

{STR([start_lat]) + ", " + STR([start_lng])}

Observation - The most popular start locations for casual riders in Chicago are densely populated areas with a lot to offer, such as the Loop, Near North Side, West Loop, Wicker Park, and Logan Square. Casual riders are also using Divvy bikes to travel to and from airports and between different stations.

Count unique end_lat and end_lng for casual riders targeted in marketing efforts.

  1. Crate a new Sheet

  2. Filter for Casual Riders: Create a filter to exclude rows where customer_type is like “member.”

  3. Aggregation: To count the occurrences of unique combinations of end_lat and end_lng, we need to create a calculated field that combines these two dimensions. In Tableau, you can create a calculated field as follows:

    • Go to Analysis menu -> Create Calculated Field.

    • Name the calculated field (e.g., LatLongCount).

    • Enter the following formula to concatenate end_lat and end_lng:

      STR([end_lat]) + ", " + STR([end_lng])

Observetion - The most densely populated areas of the city have the highest number of start locations, with the Loop and Near North Side being the most popular. This suggests that casual riders are using Divvy bikes to get around these busy areas. There are also a number of start locations outside of the city center, such as at O’Hare and Midway airports, and in the suburbs of Rosemont, Schaumburg, and Naperville. This suggests that member are using Divvy bikes to travel to and from these destinations, as well as to commute between different stations.

ACT PHASE

In this section we transition from data analysis to actionable insights. Here, we take the valuable findings extracted from our analysis and translate them into practical recommendations for real-world applications. This phase is where the rubber meets the road, as we identify the steps and strategies that can drive positive change within the organization. By distilling complex data into clear and actionable recommendations, we empower businesses to make informed decisions, optimize processes, and ultimately achieve their goals. In this phase, we bridge the gap between data analysis and meaningful impact, turning insights into action for the benefit of the organization.

Top Three Recommendations based on Analysis:

  1. Understanding User Behavior:

Tailor the user experience on the Cyclistic app or website to cater to the distinct preferences of annual members and casual riders. This might involve personalized recommendations, exclusive offers, or ride suggestions based on historical usage patterns. Also communicate the advantages of annual memberships compared to pay-as-you-go options, such as cost savings, convenience, and priority access to bikes. Utilize intuitive infographics and testimonials to convey these benefits effectively.

2. Encouraging Casual Riders to Go Annual:

Introduce a limited-time trial annual membership at a discounted rate for casual riders. This allows them to experience the convenience and savings of an annual membership before committing fully. Develop a loyalty program that rewards frequent casual riders with exclusive perks and discounts, creating an incentive to transition to annual membership. Highlight the long-term value and cost-efficiency of annual membership compared to single rides.

3. Leveraging Digital Media:

Utilize data-driven insights to craft highly targeted digital marketing campaigns. Focus on demographics, locations, and interests of casual riders who exhibit characteristics indicative of potential annual members. Create engaging and informative content, such as blog posts, videos, and social media campaigns, that highlights the benefits of becoming an annual member. Showcase real-life success stories of riders who made the switch. Collaborate with local influencers or cycling enthusiasts to endorse Cyclistic’s annual memberships. Their authentic recommendations can resonate with casual riders and motivate them to join.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the analysis of Cyclistic’s bike trip data has unveiled valuable insights into user behavior, trip patterns, and preferences. These insights offer actionable recommendations to improve the user experience, enhance marketing strategies, and optimize service coverage. By implementing the top three recommendations mentioned above, Cyclistic can effectively cater to the needs of its diverse user base, boost ridership, and drive business growth.
